attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detect possibly modified UPX magic on ELF binaries
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: @_lubiedo

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a backdoor for MIPS-based Linux IoT devices. It achieves persistence by creating a startup script (`/flash/etc/rc.d/run.d/S99telnetd`) to launch a hidden telnet daemon (`./.telnetd`). The malware manipulates firewall rules using `iptables` to drop traffic on certain ports (a common botnet behavior to prevent device takeover) and accept traffic for its own purposes. It also creates hidden files and directories (e.g., `./.p/config`) for configuration and uses the watchdog timer (`/dev/watchdog`) to maintain control.
